{{third-party|date=December 2015}} '''Allen Holub''' is a [[computer scientist]], author, educator, and consultant. He has written extensively on the [[C (programming language)|C]], [[C++]], and [[Java (programming language)|Java]] programming languages, and on [[object-oriented programming]] in general. He also writes about and teaches [[agile software development|agile development]]. He was a Contributing Editor for ''[[Dr. Dobb's Journal]]'' and ''[[JavaWorld]]'', a former columnist for ''[[SD Times]]'' (''Java Watch''), and has written the ''OO Design Process'' column for ''[[IBM DeveloperWorks]]''. He has also written for ''Microsoft Systems Journal'', ''Programmers Journal'', ''BYTE Magazine'', ''Windows Tech Journal'', ''Mac Tech Journal'', ''C Gazette'', and others.
Holub is currently{{when?|date=September 2016}} an agile process consultant, software architect, and trainer.
For several years,{{when?|date=September 2016}} he taught programming courses for the [[University of California]] Extensions in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]] and [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]]. Holub currently{{when?|date=September 2016}} conducts software design seminars and provides design consulting. His past and current clients include Autodesk, Microsoft, Stanford Linear Accelerator, Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory, Genentech, Fujitsu, Hewlett Packard, Novell, Perkin Elmer Applied Biosystems, Sybase, University of California, Pacific Bell, and [[PeopleSoft]].<ref>"[http://www.holub.com/company/clients.html]". ''Client list on Holub Associates website'' </ref>
