{{education-stub}}

'''Examen facultatum''' ([[Latin language|Latin]] for ''faculty exam''; abbreviated to ''Ex.fac.'') is, together with [[Examen philosophicum]], one of two [[Academy|academic]] [[Test (assessment)|exams]] in most [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate programmes]] at [[Norwegian universities]]. ''Examen facultatum'' is a result of [[theory of science]] being separated from ''Examen philosophicum'' as an independent type of course before 2000. Whereas ''Examen philosophicum'' trains [[student]]s in [[philosophy]] and [[Critical thinking|structured thinking]], ''Examen facultatum'' aims at teaching students how to write academic texts, normally focussing on the [[Branches of science|scientific branch]] of each [[Faculty (division)|faculty]] and on the [[Discipline (academia)|field of study]] of each undergraduate programme.<ref name="SNL"/><ref name="St.meld. 27"/> It is common for universities to have a general course and a course specific part that intertwine with any chosen study as part of ''Examen philosophicum''.
''Examen facultatum'' as a compulsory course is legally based in [[Statutory instrument|royal regulations]] for each university, for example ''Regulations of 20 December 2005 No. 1798 on Studies and Exams at the University of Oslo'' in the case of the [[University of Oslo]].<ref name="Regulations 20122005 No 1798"/> Both ''Examen facultatum'' and ''Examen philosophicum'' are compulsory parts of most [[bachelor's degree]]s in [[Norway]]: mainly [[professional studies]] at [[University college (Scandinavia)|university colleges]] and [[natural science]] studies at [[Norwegian universities|universities]] are exempt from either one or both.
